Persons assigned male at birth from the Solomon Islands, Tokelau, Tonga, Tuvalu, and Wallis and Futuna who are characterized as feminine.

A term used by some Indigenous Australians, Torres Strait Islanders, and Māori people similarly to its North American counterpart, descibring such a person who is non-cisgender, non-binary or gender-variant (especially one belonging to a traditional tribal third-gender, fourth-gender or transgender category), or who is non-heterosexual.
Bisexual when considered as a specific identity.
Gay when considered as a specific identity.
Lesbian when considered as a specific identity.
Heterosexual when considered as a specific identity.
Two-Spirit described as a primarily sexual identity which is non-heterosexual.

Depending on context, Two-Spirit may refer to a gender identity and/or role, a sexual orientation and/or sexuality, both, or neither. This entry is intended to represent cases which context is sexual identity. Use more specific entries where applicable.
A Native (North) American who is non-heterosexual or belongs to a specific sexual orientation group related to their culture.

Depending on context, Two-Spirit may refer to a gender identity and/or role, a sexual orientation and/or sexuality, both, or neither. This entry is intended to represent cases which context is sexual orientation. Use more specific entries where applicable.
Queer when considered as a specific identity.

Cultural variance is cultural behavior or expression exhibited by an individual or group that does not match cultural/social cultural norms and/or expectations, either from a cultural in-group perspective or from a cultural out-group perspective.
The term "Two Spirit" was adopted by consensus in 1990 at an international gay and lesbian Indigenous gathering as a replacement for the inappropriate and outdated term "berdache".

Depending on context, Two-Spirit may refer to a gender identity and/or role, a sexual orientation and/or sexuality, both, or neither. This entry is intended to represent cases which context is unknown or unspecified. Use more specific entries where applicable.
A political ideology which expresses deviation which does not accord with a mainstream doctrine for a given time and/or area.
A deviationist political ideology which is based upon significant revision of fundamental premises of a given time and/or place, especially those which ideologies which are irrational in nature.
A form of deviationism which imploys denial of fundamental premises, often irrationally.
A form of deviationist ideology predicated on beliefs held with unquestionable certainty, often without critical interrogation of those beliefs.

A particular subtype of COVID-19 denialism focused on denial of the effectiveness of COVID-19 vaccines, followed by claims that other, unproven and unscientific folk remedies (such as essential oils, bleach, hydroxychloroquine, ivermectin) can effect the course of COVID-19 in any discernible way.

The false belief that vaccines do not work, or that some aspect of the vaccines has been exaggerated or fabricated by the medical community or world governments, such as the claim that vaccines cause autism or gender dysphoria, among other things.
Persons organized by their gender modality.
Persons organized by disability status.
Persons organized by transition status.
A transgender person who has retransitioned after a period of detransition, for any reason.
A transgender person who has detransitioned for any reason, but still considers themself transgender.
Any person, regardless of current gender modality, who has detransitioned.
Any person, regardless of current gender modality, who has retransitioned.
A cisgender person who has detransitioned for any reason, and considers themself to be cisgender.
Persons organized by neurotype.
Discrimination against asexual spectrum persons.
Fear, dislike, or hatred of aromantic people and/or human aromanticism.
Discrimination against non-monogamous persons.
An ideology which advocates in regard to the primacy of or the desirability of social norms, or the current socio-political norm; contrast with deviationism.
Any assumption of an age-based norm and particularly the assumption that adults and adult experiences are normative while children and childish experiences are consequently deviant or other.
The ideology that metropolitan or urban areas and populations are prioritized over other areas, such as those that are rural or suburban.
Normativity in LGBTQIA+ communities in which the metropolitan is prioritized as a mode of acceptance, i.e. the only way of achieving happiness and open existence.
Any of various kinds of normativity based on age.
Any of various kinds of normativity based on environment.
Any of various kinds of normativity based on some aspect of gender.
